Last year, the Gemini meteor shower "Falling Petals" left a deep impression on people, but this year the Gemini meteor shower will be interfered with by moonlight, reducing its spectacle.
It is the 14th day of the lunar calendar on November 11th, a waxing gibbous moon, bright moonlight will cause interference to the observation, luckily the moon will set in the later part of the night, and at this time, the radiation of the Gemini meteor shower will elevate to a higher degree.
Friends who like meteor showers can observe them in the few hours after midnight when the moon sets, but they should be sure to stay warm and safe.
